{{mergeto|Sebastiano Serlio|discuss=Talk:Sebastiano Serlio#Merger proposal|date=July 2018}} [[File:Tutte l'opere d'architettura MET DP109531.jpg|thumb|A page from the seventh book]] [[File:Sebastiano Serlio - Ottavo libro d’architettura. Della castrametatione di Polybio.jpg|thumb|Two pages from the eighth book]] '''''Tutte l'opere d'architettura et prospetiva''''' (''All the Works of Architecture and Perspective'') is an [[architecture|architectural]] [[treatise]] by [[Italy|Italian]] [[Renaissance]] architect [[Sebastiano Serlio]] (1475-1554). Serlio is sometimes regarded as one of the most important. The treatise is composed of eight [[book]]s, the sixth of which was lost for some centuries and the eighth of which was not published until relatively recently. The eighth book is not always considered to be part of the treatise. The first five books cover Serlio's works on [[geometry]], [[Perspective (graphical)|perspective]], [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] antiquity, the [[Classical order|Orders]] and [[Church (building)|church]] design. The sixth illustrates domestic designs ranging from [[peasant]] huts to royal palaces, providing a unique record of Renaissance house types, including up-to-date [[fortress]]es for [[tyrant]]s and mercenaries as well as Serlio's unbuilt design for the [[Louvre]]. The seventh book illustrates a range of common design problems ignored by past theorists, including how to remodel, or 'restore', [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] [[façade]]s following antique principles of [[symmetry]] and [[Proportion (architecture)|proportion]]. The eighth book, called "'''Castrametation of the Romans'''", reconstructs a Roman encampment after the description by [[Polybius]], followed by a military [[city]] and monumental [[bridge]] supposedly built by the Emperor [[Trajan]]. With its [[Forum (Roman)|forum]], [[consul]]'s palace and [[Roman baths|baths]], the book is part-fantasy and part-[[archaeology]], quite unlike Serlio's other more practical works. <ref> {{cite journal |url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science?_ob=ArticleURL&_udi=B6V70-4FK3GMP-2&_user=10&_rdoc=1&_fmt=&_orig=search&_sort=d&view=c&_acct=C000050221&_version=1&_urlVersion=0&_userid=10&md5=0cf7cc18c6ca43b616360a77edb22123 |title= From proportion to balance: the background to symmetry in science |accessdate=2008-05-20 |doi=10.1016/j.shpsa.2004.12.001 |volume=36 |journal=Studies in History and Philosophy of Science Part A |pages=1–21 |year= 2005 |last1= Hon |first1= Giora |last2= Goldstein |first2= Bernard R. }} </ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Architectural history]] [[Category:1537 works]]

{{refimprove|date=April 2018}} A '''vactrain''' (or '''vacuum tube train''') is a proposed design for very-[[high-speed rail]] transportation. It is a [[maglev]] (magnetic levitation) line using partly [[vacuum|evacuated]] tubes or tunnels. Reduced air resistance could permit vactrains to travel at very high speeds with relatively little power—up to {{convert|4000|–|5000|mph|abbr=on|order=flip}}. This is 5–6 times the [[speed of sound]] in Earth's atmosphere at sea level.<ref name="eett">{{cite episode|title=Transatlantic Tunnel |episodelink=<!-- for wikiarticle about episode --> |url=http://dsc.discovery.com/convergence/engineering/transatlantictunnel/interactive/interactive.html |series=Extreme Engineering |serieslink=Extreme Engineering |credits=Joseph Giotta (Narrator), Powderhouse Productions |network=[[Discovery Channel]] |airdate=April 16, 2003 |transcripturl= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927014656/http://dsc.discovery.com/convergence/engineering/transatlantictunnel/interactive/interactive.html |archivedate=September 27, 2011 }}</ref> Vactrains might use [[Gravity train|gravity]] to assist their acceleration. If these trains achieve the predicted speeds, they could surpass [[aircraft]] as the world's fastest mode of public transportation.
However, without major advances in tunneling and other technology, vactrains would be prohibitively expensive.{{cn|date=November 2018}}
==18th century== {{main|Atmospheric railway}} In 1799, [[George Medhurst]] of London conceived of and patented an [[Atmospheric railway#Medhurst | atmospheric railway]] that could convey people or cargo through pressurized or evacuated tubes. The early atmospheric railways and pneumatic tube transport systems (such as the [[Dalkey Atmospheric Railway]]) relied on steam power for propulsion.
==19th century== In 1888, [[Michel Verne]], son of [[Jules Verne]], imagined a submarine pneumatic tube transport system that could propel a passenger capsule at speeds up to 1800 km/h under the Atlantic Ocean in a short story called "An Express of the Future".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks06/0606611h.html | title=An Express of the Future | first=Michel | last=Verne}}</ref>
==20th century== The vactrain proper was invented by [[Robert Goddard]] as a freshman at [[Worcester Polytechnic Institute]] in the United States in 1904.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/the-scifi-story-robert-h-goddard-published-100-years-a-1494959842 | title=The SciFi Story Robert H. Goddard Published 100 Years Ago | website=gizmodo.com}}</ref> Goddard subsequently refined the idea in a 1906 short story called "The High-Speed Bet" which was summarized and published in a Scientific American editorial in 1909 called "The Limit of Rapid Transit". Esther, his wife, was granted a US patent for the vactrain in 1950, five years after his death.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.google.com/patents/US2511979 | title=Vacuum tube transportation system | website=patents.google.com | publisher=Google}}</ref>
In 1909, Russian professor {{Interlanguage link multi|Boris Weinberg|ru|3=Вейнберг, Борис Петрович}} built the world's first model of his proposed version of the vactrain at [[Tomsk Polytechnic University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://veinberg.o7.ru/ |title=Движение без трения. pre-α |trans-title=Motion without friction. pre-α |first=Boris |last=Weinberg |accessdate=November 24, 2015 |language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:Popular_Science_Monthly_Volume_90.djvu/721 |title=Five Hundred Miles an Hour |first=Boris |last=Weinberg |journal=Popular Science Monthly |year=1917 |volume=90 |pages=705–708}}</ref> He later published a vactrain concept in 1914 in the book ''Motion without friction (airless electric way)''.
In 1955, Polish science-fiction writer [[Stanisław Lem]] in a novel ''The Magellan Nebula'' wrote about intercontinental vactrain called "organowiec", which moved in a transparent tube at a speed higher than 1,666&nbsp;km/h. Later in April 1962, the vactrain appears in the story "Mercenary" by [[Mack Reynolds]],<ref>{{cite journal|first = Mack|last = Reynolds|title = Mercenary|date = April 1962|publisher = [[Analog Science Fiction and Fact]]|url = http://www.gutenberg.org/files/24370/24370-h/24370-h.htm|accessdate=January 19, 2015}}</ref> where he mentions Vacuum Tube Transport in passing.
During the 1970s, a leading vactrain advocate, [[Robert M. Salter]] of [[RAND]], published a series of elaborate engineering articles.<ref>{{Citation|first = Robert M.|last = Salter|author-link = Robert M. Salter|title = The Very High Speed Transit System|date = August 1972|publisher = [[RAND Corporation]]|url = https://www.rand.org/pubs/papers/P4874.html|accessdate = September 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|first = Robert M.|last = Salter|author-link = Robert M. Salter|title = Trans-Planetary Subway Systems: A Burgeoning Capability|date = February 1978|publisher = [[RAND Corporation]]|url = https://www.rand.org/pubs/papers/P6092.html|accessdate = September 28, 2011}}</ref>
An interview with Robert Salter appeared in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' (June 11, 1972). He discussed, in detail, the relative ease with which the [[U.S. government]] could build a tube shuttle system using technologies available at that time. Maglev being poorly developed at the time, he proposed steel wheels. The chamber's door to the tube would be opened, and enough air admitted behind to accelerate the train into the tube. Gravity would further accelerate the departing train down to cruise level. Rising from cruise level, the arriving train would decelerate by compressing the rarefied air ahead of it, which would be vented. Pumps at the stations would make up for losses due to friction or air escaping around the edges of the train, the train itself requiring no motor. This combination of modified (shallow) [[gravity train]] and [[atmospheric railway]] propulsion would consume little [[energy]] but limit the system to subsonic speeds, hence initial routes of tens or hundreds of miles or kilometers rather than transcontinental distances were proposed.{{fact|date=April 2018}}
Trains were to require no [[Railway coupling|coupler]]s, each car being directly welded, bolted, or otherwise firmly connected to the next, the route calling for no more bending than the flexibility of steel could easily handle. At the end of the line the train would be moved sideways into the end chamber of the return tube. The railway would have both an inner evacuated tube and an outer tunnel. At cruise depth, the space between would have enough water to float the vacuum tube, softening the ride.{{fact|date=April 2018}}
A route through the [[Northeast Megalopolis]] was laid out, with nine stations, one each in the [[Washington DC|District of Columbia]], [[Maryland]], [[Delaware]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Rhode Island]], [[Massachusetts]], and two in [[Connecticut]]. [[Commuter rail]] systems were mapped for the [[San Francisco]] and New York areas, the commuter version having longer, heavier trains, to be propelled less by air and more by gravity than the intercity version. The New York system was to have three lines, terminating in [[Babylon (village), New York|Babylon]], [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]], [[Huntington, New York|Huntington]], [[Elizabeth, New Jersey|Elizabeth]], [[White Plains, New York|White Plains]], and [[St. George, Staten Island|St. George]].{{fact|date=April 2018}}
Salter pointed out how such a system would help reduce the environmental damage being done to the atmosphere by [[aviation]] and surface transportation. He called underground Very High Speed Transportation (tube shuttles) his nation's "logical next step". The plans were never taken to the next stage.{{fact|date=April 2018}}
At the time these reports were published, national prestige was an issue as [[Japan]] had been operating its showcase [[shinkansen|bullet train]] for several years and [[maglev train]] research was hot technology. The American ''Planetran'' would establish transcontinental subway service in the United States and provide a commute from [[Los Angeles]] to [[New York City]] in one hour. The tunnel would be buried to a depth of several hundred feet in solid rock formations. Construction would make use of [[laser]]s to ensure alignment and use [[tungsten]] probes to melt through [[igneous]] rock formations. The tunnel would maintain a partial vacuum to minimize [[Drag (physics)|drag]]. A trip would average {{convert|3000|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} and subject passengers to accelerations up to 1.4 times that of gravity, requiring the use of [[gimbal]]led compartments. Enormous construction costs (estimated as high as US$1 trillion) were the primary reason why Salter's proposal was never built.{{fact|date=April 2018}}
[[File:Swissmetro Network 2005.png|thumb|[[Swissmetro]] as proposed in 2005]] Starting in the late 1970s and early 1980s, the [[Swissmetro]] was proposed to leverage the invention of the experimental German [[Transrapid]] maglev train, and operate in large underground tunnels reduced to the pressure altitude of {{convert|68000|ft|m|order=flip|abbr=on}} at which the [[Concorde]] SST was certified to fly.{{fact|date=April 2018}}
In the 1980s, [[Frank P. Davidson]], a founder and chairman of the [[Channel Tunnel]] project, and Japanese engineer {{Interlanguage link multi|Yoshihiro Kyotani|ja|3=京谷好泰}} tackled the transoceanic problems with a proposal to float a tube above the ocean floor, anchored with cables (a [[submerged floating tunnel]]). The transit tube would remain at least {{convert|1000|ft|m|abbr=on|order=flip}} below the ocean surface to avoid water turbulence.{{fact|date=April 2018}}
On November 18, 1991, [[Gerard K. O'Neill]] filed a patent application for a vactrain system. He called the company he wanted to form ''VSE International'', for velocity, silence, and efficiency.<ref name="Dyson93p98">{{harvnb|Dyson|1993|p=98}}</ref> However, the concept itself he called ''[[Magnetic Flight]]''. The vehicles, instead of running on a pair of tracks, would be elevated using electromagnetic force by a single track within a tube (permanent magnets in the track, with variable magnets on the vehicle), and propelled by electromagnetic forces through tunnels. He estimated the trains could reach speeds of up to {{convert|2,500|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} – about five times faster than a jet airliner – if the air was evacuated from the tunnels.<ref>{{harvnb|Daniels|1992}}</ref> To obtain such speeds, the vehicle would accelerate for the first half of the trip, and then decelerate for the second half of the trip. The acceleration was planned to be a maximum of about one-half of the force of gravity. O'Neill planned to build a network of stations connected by these tunnels, but he died two years before his first patent on it was granted.<ref name="Dyson93p98"/>
==21st century== [[James R. Powell]], former co-inventor of [[superconducting]] [[maglev]] in the 1960s, has since 2001 led investigation of a concept for using a maglev vactrain for [[space launch]] (theoretically two orders of magnitude less marginal cost than present rockets), where the [[StarTram]] proposal would have vehicles reach up to {{convert|8900|to|19600|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} within an acceleration tunnel (lengthy to limit [[g-force]]s), considering boring through the ice sheet in Antarctica for lower anticipated expense than in rock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startram.com/resources|title=StarTram2010|publisher=startram.com|accessdate=April 28, 2011}}</ref>
[[ET3 Global Alliance|ET3]] claim to have achieved some work that resulted in a patent on "evacuated tube transport technology" which was granted in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.et3.com |title=Why ET3? {{!}} Evacuated Tube Transport Technologies |publisher=ET3 |location=US |date=2013 |access-date=October 9, 2017}}</ref> They presented their idea 2013 on public stage.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=http://www.ideacity.ca/video/daryl-oster-speedy-travel-vacuum-tube/ |title=Speedy Travel in a Vaccuum Tube |first=Daryl |last=Oster |via=Idea City |location=US |date=October 9, 2013 |access-date=October 9, 2017}}</ref>
[[Elon Musk]], CEO of Tesla and SpaceX, champions the vactrain concept under the term [[hyperloop]]. An agreement was signed in 2017 to co-develop a hyperloop line between Seoul and Busan in South Korea.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.imeche.org/news/news-article/investment-in-hyperloop-routes-speeds-up |title=Investment in hyperloop routes speeds up |first=Jørn |last=Madslien |publisher=Institute of Mechanical Engineers |location=UK |date=July 19, 2017 |access-date=August 11, 2017}}</ref>
[[TransPod]] is a Canadian company designing and manufacturing ultra-high-speed tube transportation technology and vehicles.<ref name="transpodabout">{{cite web|title=About TransPod|url=https://transpodhyperloop.com/about-transpod/|website=TransPod|publisher=TransPod Inc|accessdate=October 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005050639/https://transpodhyperloop.com/about-transpod/|archive-date=October 5, 2017|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> TransPod vehicles are being designed to travel at over 1000 km/h between cities using fully electric propulsion and zero need for fossil fuels. Unlike the hyperloop vactrain concept, the TransPod system uses moving electromagnetic fields to propel the vehicles with stable levitation off the bottom surface, rather than compressed air.<ref name="procedia">{{cite journal|last1=Janzen|first1=Ryan|title=TransPod Ultra-High-Speed Tube Transportation: Dynamics of Vehicles and Infrastructure|journal=Procedia Engineering|date=2017|volume=199|pages=8-17|url=http://transpodresearch.org/files/docs/TransPod_ProcediaEngineering2017_Janzen.pdf|accessdate=October 4, 2017|ref=procedia}}</ref> In September 2017, TransPod released a scientific peer-reviewed publication in the journal Procedia Engineering.<ref name="scidirect">{{cite web|title=TransPod Ultra-High-Speed Tube Transportation: Dynamics of Vehicles and Infrastructure|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S187770581733583X|website=Science Direct|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> The paper was premiered at the [[European Association for Structural Dynamics|EASD]] EURODYN 2017 conference,<ref name="eurodynlectures">{{cite web|title=Keynote Lectures - Eurodyn|url=https://www.eurodyn2017.it/keynote-lectures/|website=Eurodyn 2017|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> and presents the physics of the TransPod system.<ref name="procedia"/>
